'''Petr Janda''' (born 5 January 1975) is a [[Czechs|Czech]] [[architect]]. He studied at the [[Czech Technical University in Prague]] (1993–2001) and is also a graduate of the Monumental Art Studio of Professor [[Aleš Veselý]] at the [[Academy of Fine Arts, Prague|Academy of Fine Arts]] (1997–2003).

He started to work with ''A 69 Architects'', later he was one of the founding members of ''sporadical''{{sic|?}} art studio. Since March 2008 he has run his own ''brainwork'' art studio. In 2011 he became a member of the board of the Czech Chamber of Architects.

== Works ==
[[File:Památník obětem komunismu Liberec.jpg|thumb|left|Memorial to the victims of communism, Liberec]]
* Memorial to the floods, [[Otrokovice]] (1998) 
* Memorial to the victims of [[communism]], [[Liberec]](2006) 
* Lazyhouse, [[Zlín]] (2007–)
* Flowhouse, [[Tečovice]] (2008–)
* Golf Academy [[Olomouc]] (2010–)
* (A)VOID Floating - floating pavilion, [[Prague]] (2011–)

[[File:Kostel Krista Spasitele a KC Barrandov.jpg|thumb|Proposal of the Church of Christ the Redeemer in Prague]]

== Awards ==
* 2013 National Prize '''BigMat 2013''' (BigMat ’13 International Architecture Award) – Memorial to the victims of communism, Liberec<ref>[http://www.architectureaward.bigmat.com/en/winners BigMat ´13 International Architecture Award Winners]</ref> 
* 2013 - 2nd–3rd Prize – Roman Catholic Church of Christ the Redeemer, Prague 
* 2009 - 1st Prize Aboard city 2 Botel, [[Smíchov]], Prague 
* 2007 - 1st Prize Aboard city 1 Botel, [[Vyšehrad]], Prague 
* 2007 - National Architecture Award (Grand Prix architektů) - Memorial to the victims of communism, Liberec<ref>[http://www.grandprix-architektu.cz/cz/grandprix-architektu/archiv/gpa-2007/laureati/v3--pamatnik-obetem-komunismu/c452 Památník obětem komunismu], Grand Prix Architektů, 2007 (in Czech)</ref>
* 2007 - 2nd Prize, [[Nikola Tesla]] Memorial, Prague 
* 2000 - 3rd Prize, Memorial to the victims of the totalitarian regime, Prague 
* 1999 - 2nd Prize, [[Jan Palach]] and [[Jan Zajíc]] Memorial, [[Wenceslas Square]], Prague

